    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="474"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d474">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.7111/58.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName type="to">Page</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 186.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 9, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatches Nos.
                    251 and 252, of February 21 and 23, respectively, in which you enclose copies of
                    notes received by you from the British Minister for Foreign Affairs asking that
                    steps be taken to prevent the departure for the Gold Coast Colony of the
                    followers of one “Chief Sam,” who claims to be an African chief.</p>
                <p>The Department has transmitted copies of your despatches to the Governor of
                    Oklahoma, the Attorney General and the Postmaster General and has been informed
                    by the Attorney General that his Department is unable to take any action against
                    “Chief Sam.” The Post Office Department, however, is making an investigation of
                    the matter to determine whether “Chief Sam “has made fraudulent use of the
                    United States mails.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John E. Osborne</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
